Fitting pointwise GEVD distributions

We first load the EnvStats package and create custom function to extract parameters directly.

library(EnvStats)
gevd_pars <- function(x){egevd(x)$parameters}

Now performing the estimation per column in the data frame.

parameters <- sapply(select(max_data, -YEAR), gevd_pars)%>%t()%>%as.data.frame()

Creating the data frame that contains the GEVD parameters per weather station…

parameters$"Station Name" <- row.names(parameters)
stations_pars <- full_join(stations,parameters, by = "Station Name")
stations_pars

Visualization

library(tidyverse)
rl_gathered <- stations_pars |> 
    mutate(rl_5 = qgevd(1-1/5, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape),
           rl_50 = qgevd(1-1/50, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape),
           rl_100 = qgevd(1-1/100, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape)) |> 
    select(`Station Name`, LAT, LON, rl_5, rl_50, rl_100) |> 
    pivot_longer(cols= c(rl_5, rl_50, rl_100), 
                 names_to = "Return Period",
                 values_to = "Return Level") |> 
    mutate("Return Period" = ordered(`Return Period`, levels = c("rl_5", "rl_50", "rl_100")))
ph_map +
    geom_point(data = rl_gathered, aes(x = LON, y = LAT, color = `Return Level`))+
    facet_wrap(.~`Return Period`)+
    scale_color_viridis_c()+
    theme_bw()

Spatial Interpolation

Recall that the stations_pars data frame contains longitude and latitude coordinates of each weather station and the corresponding estimated GEVD parameters of the annual maxima. This will be the source data for interpolation.

stations_pars

For a short demonstration of hierarchical spatial interpolation of extremes, we will perform three spatial interpolation procedures on the GEV parameters \(\mu,\sigma,\xi\) . Values will be assigned on a 30 x 50 grid, masked by the Philippines land boundaries.

library(sp)
stations_pars_spdf <- SpatialPointsDataFrame(stations_pars,
                                             coords = stations[,c("LON", "LAT")])

ph_grid <- expand.grid(x = seq(from = min(provinces$long), 
                               to = max(provinces$long), length.out = 80),
                       y = seq(from = min(provinces$lat),
                               to = max(provinces$lat), length.out = 100))
coordinates(ph_grid) <- ~x + y

Inverse Distance Weighting

idw_loc   <- gstat::idw(location ~ 1, stations_pars_spdf, ph_grid, idp = 2.0)
## [inverse distance weighted interpolation]
idw_scale <- gstat::idw(scale ~ 1, stations_pars_spdf, ph_grid, idp = 2.0)
## [inverse distance weighted interpolation]
idw_shape <- gstat::idw(shape ~ 1, stations_pars_spdf, ph_grid, idp = 2.0)
## [inverse distance weighted interpolation]
df_idw <- data.frame(x = ph_grid$x, y = ph_grid$y,
                     location = idw_loc$var1.pred,
                     scale = idw_scale$var1.pred,
                     shape = idw_shape$var1.pred)

Computation of return level values

rl_idw <- df_idw |> 
    mutate(rl_5 = qgevd(1-1/5, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape),
           rl_50 = qgevd(1-1/50, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape),
           rl_100 = qgevd(1-1/100, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape)) |> 
    select(x, y, rl_5, rl_50, rl_100) |> 
    pivot_longer(cols= c(rl_5, rl_50, rl_100), 
                 names_to = "Return Period",
                 values_to = "Return Level") |> 
    mutate("Return Period" = ordered(`Return Period`, levels = c("rl_5", "rl_50", "rl_100")))
rl_idw
ggplot()+
    geom_raster(data = rl_idw, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = `Return Level`))+
    scale_fill_viridis_c(limits = c(0, max(rl_idw$`Return Level`)))+
    coord_fixed()+
    theme_bw()+
    facet_wrap(.~`Return Period`)+
    geom_polygon(data = provinces, aes( x = long, y = lat,
                                          group = group), fill="gray", alpha = 0.5)

Kriging

library(gstat)
v_loc <- variogram(location ~ 1, stations_pars_spdf)
fit_loc <- fit.variogram(v_loc, vgm(model = "Sph"))
## Warning in fit.variogram(v_loc, vgm(model = "Sph")): singular model in variogram
## fit
krig_loc   <- gstat::krige(location ~ 1,
                           stations_pars_spdf,
                           ph_grid,
                           model = fit_loc)
## [using ordinary kriging]
v_scale <- variogram(scale ~ 1, stations_pars_spdf)
fit_scale <- fit.variogram(v_scale, vgm(model = "Sph"))
krig_scale <- gstat::krige(scale ~ 1,
                           stations_pars_spdf,
                           ph_grid,
                           model = fit_scale)
## [using ordinary kriging]
v_shape <- variogram(shape ~ 1, stations_pars_spdf)
fit_shape <- fit.variogram(v_shape, vgm(model = "Sph"))
krig_shape <- gstat::krige(shape ~ 1,
                           stations_pars_spdf,
                           ph_grid,
                           model = fit_shape)
## [using ordinary kriging]
df_krig <- data.frame(x = ph_grid$x, y = ph_grid$y,
                     location = krig_loc$var1.pred,
                     scale = krig_scale$var1.pred,
                     shape = krig_shape$var1.pred)

Computation of return level values

rl_krig <- df_krig |> 
    mutate(rl_5 = qgevd(1-1/5, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape),
           rl_50 = qgevd(1-1/50, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape),
           rl_100 = qgevd(1-1/100, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape)) |> 
    select(x, y, rl_5, rl_50, rl_100) |> 
    pivot_longer(cols= c(rl_5, rl_50, rl_100), 
                 names_to = "Return Period",
                 values_to = "Return Level") |> 
    mutate("Return Period" = ordered(`Return Period`, levels = c("rl_5", "rl_50", "rl_100")))
rl_idw
ggplot()+
    geom_raster(data = rl_krig, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = `Return Level`))+

Spline

library(fields)
## Warning: package 'fields' was built under R version 4.2.3
spline_loc   <- Tps(coordinates(stations_pars_spdf),
                    stations_pars_spdf$location, lambda = 0)
spline_scale   <- Tps(coordinates(stations_pars_spdf),
                    stations_pars_spdf$scale, lambda = 0)
spline_shape   <- Tps(coordinates(stations_pars_spdf),
                    stations_pars_spdf$shape, lambda = 0)
df_spline <- as.data.frame(ph_grid) |> 
    mutate(location = predict(spline_loc, as.data.frame(ph_grid)),
           scale  = predict(spline_scale, as.data.frame(ph_grid)),
           shape = predict(spline_shape, as.data.frame(ph_grid)))

Computation of return level values

           rl_50 = qgevd(1-1/50, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape),
           rl_100 = qgevd(1-1/100, location = location, scale = scale, shape = shape)) |> 
    select(x, y, rl_5, rl_50, rl_100) |> 
    pivot_longer(cols= c(rl_5, rl_50, rl_100), 
                 names_to = "Return Period",
                 values_to = "Return Level") |> 
    mutate("Return Period" = ordered(`Return Period`, levels = c("rl_5", "rl_50", "rl_100")))
rl_idw
ggplot()+

In the spline interpolation, from the graphs, there is a tendency that this model will over estimate when it comes to extrapolation of values outside the study region

Model Evaluation

We perform a jack-knife estimate of the parameters on station \(i\) to obtain evaluation metrics. That is, using the different spatial interpolation procedures, we spatially interpolate the parameters \(\{\tilde{\mu},\tilde{\sigma}, \tilde{\xi}\}\) on station \(i\) while assuming that this station is missing. R We will append the interpolated parameters \(\{\tilde{\mu}_\alpha,\tilde{\sigma}_\alpha, \tilde{\xi}_\alpha\},\alpha\in\{\text{idw},\text{krig},\text{spline}\}\) on this data frame.

We then compare the quantiles of \(GEVD(\{\tilde{\mu}_\alpha,\tilde{\sigma}_\alpha, \tilde{\xi}_\alpha\}\) to the empirical quantiles of the observed data.
